Londen Jan Kent & comp
S Sence my last of 5 cur recd. yours of 19 past with bill of
loadinge & invoyce of N26 aboard Corn markens, with I suppoce
with the rest arrived att ostend, sure you had time enough for the
frieses beence you had itt for the spesclothes now patience, lett then
come for Rotterdam, or amst p the first depasting & if this come
in time to be hadded 2 a 3 white or light grayes if to be had
wonder you make no mention of the convous att hull of oh
holland wee had last night a violeut stoim out of the nord west
ifitt hath been so att zea will cause losses, god preserve iis
for wee can not regaine much, all thinges are so undersold by
gaysacker that he must needs be cheaper served from you, or
I can not understand itt, for I have seen goods sold lheapep then
mine cost mee though boath from you interint, j care
no much these dangerous timm to sell much Irest

Londen John Kent & comp
sence mj bast of 8 cuf non from you, I understand that the
nott convoye for london is sbill att this side, so that you hae
time enough fort the frises amorghts with I question not butt you
shall finde the cohite erayes I desire you not to cese the rott
kinde to mee, you might, have sent a pack soy the ostend convoy, butt
itt zeems you minde more your new freinds then the old, I know you have
sent severall frises by this convoy for ostend, & by my haveing non,
loose the opportunibie, therefore loose no opporthnitre to ship them, tt
vee understand, that convoyes are to come from london to de macke for
the king, if so send theen p first I wonder wee heare notting h from
the nord. inclosed £250:- on S Joseph Kerne & £102:19: on
lierens & eruger procure the neewfull & advise
what passes I s

heb selve niet en verneme, & van ue daer over geen schrijven, soo haest het
